<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-04-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-04-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="511" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d511">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Pike</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Seward</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 163.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">United States Legation.</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Hague,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-04-27"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 27, 1865.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> The horrible news of to-day by telegraph,
                            after two weeks of rejoicing, overwhelms me so completely that I find
                            myself wholly unable to do more than to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            despatches Nos. 217 to 224, inclusive.</p>
                        <p>With the profoundest emotions of sympathy, and the most agonizing
                            apprehensions for your own condition, I remain, with great respect, your
                            most obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>JAMES S. PIKE.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">William H. Seward,</hi>
                                <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State, Washington.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>